In this verse, the artist is referring to his ex's scar tissue, presumably from past trauma of some kind. He implies that he wishes the person he is addressing could see the scar tissue as a reminder of his ex, and insinuates that it would make the person fear him. He also labels his ex "sarcastic mister know-it-all," a descriptor which could be a metaphor for his ex's unforgiving behavior or simply describe a personality trait. The verse closes with the artist saying "close your eyes and I'll kiss you" as a means of comfort, promise, or simply a sign of love.

This verse conveys a sense of pain, longing, and unwavering dedication despite past trauma. It also conveys love and devotion despite the circumstances.
The specific reference to "scar tissue" may refer to the song of the same name by the Red Hot Chili Peppers, a band which has a history of addressing personal trauma and pushing past pain.
This verse follows a rhyming couplet structure, showcasing a natural pair of ideas which enhance the sense of emotion felt in the lyrics.

Broken hearts, love, and unresolved trauma are themes that have been addressed in music as far back as the blues, and this verse appears to draw upon those themes in a way that modern audiences can relate to.

A man is talking about his ex and wishing that the person he is addressing could see his ex's scar tissue in order to be scared of him. He then goes on to show his devotion to this person by offering a comforting kiss. This verse begins and ends with the same idea, providing symmetry and balance to the overall emotion of the lyrics.

This verse implies that the speaker puts his pain and trauma from his past in perspective in order to prioritize the love he has in the present. It could also allude to the idea that love can heal and bring about emotional growth, suggesting that the resolution of past hurt can be a means of strengthening current relationships.
